els came to appear in its various versions, explaining how it went through a series of transformations as it reached new audiences in order to serve as both a response to previous writings about the East and an important voice in the medieval conversation about the nature and limits of the world. Higgins offers a palimpsestic reading of this "multi-text" that demonstrates not only how the original French author overwrote his precursors but also how subsequent translators molded the material to serve their own ideological agendas.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 23. Jun 2020) 0aGeography, Medieval, in literature. 0aTravel, Medieval. 0aTravelers' writings, EnglishxHistory and criticism. 4aCultural Studies. 4aLiterature. 4aMedieval and Renaissance Studies. 7aLITERARY CRITICISM / Medieval.2bisacsh08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertPenn Press eBook Package Complete Collectionz978311041345808iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertPenn Press eBook-Package Literaturez978311041354008iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertPenn eBook Package Archive 1898-1999 (pre Pub)z978311044252640uhttps://doi.org/10.9783/978081220226740uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780812202267423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/cover/covers/9780812202267.jpg  a978-3-11-041345-8  Penn Press eBook Package Complete Collection  a978-3-11-041354-0  Penn Press eBook-Package Literature  a978-3-11-044252-6  Penn eBook Package Archive 1898-1999c1898d1999  aEBA_BACKALL  aEBA_CL_LT  aEBA_EBACKALL  aEBA_EBKALL  aEBA_ECL_LT  aEBA_EEBKALL  aEBA_ESSHALL  aEBA_PPALL  aEBA_SSHALL  aGBV-deGruyter-alles  aPDA11SSHE  aPDA13ENGE  aPDA17SSHEE  aPDA5EBK